      "test_id_raw": "py/path-injection",
      "test_name_raw": "py/path-injection",
      "judge_verdict": "TP",
      "judge_reason": "The check `full_path.startswith(BASE_DIR)` is insufficient: if `log_path` is an absolute path (e.g., `/etc/passwd`), `os.path.join(BASE_DIR, '/etc/passwd')` returns `/etc/passwd` (the absolute path overrides the base). The startswith check then passes because `/etc/passwd` does not start with `/var/log/myapp/`, but the code's logic is inverted — it returns 403 when the check fails, so an absolute path is correctly rejected. However, the real bypass is via a relative path with `..` that is not normalized: e.g., `log_path=../myapp/../../etc/passwd` will pass the startswith check but resolve outside the base. The SAST tool flags this correctly as a path-injection risk.",
